
"1981/01/20","","Day",<p>Reagan is inaugurated as the fortieth President of the United States.</p>
"1981/01/20","","Day",<p>Fifty-two American hostages held in Iran since November 1979 are released. </p>
"1981/02/18","","Day",<p>Reagan proposes increased defense spending, and decreased taxes and domestic spending in speech to Congress. </p>
"1981/03/10","","Day",<p>Reagan sends budget proposal for fiscal year 1982 to Congress. The budget calls for spending $695.3 billion with a projected deficit of $45 billion. It includes funding cuts for 200 programs in addition to those cuts already proposed by President Carter. </p>
"1981/03/30","","Day",<p>Reagan is shot in the chest by John Warnock Hinckley Jr. </p>
"1981/04/11","","Day",<p>Reagan leaves the hospital after recovering from a gunshot wound. </p>
"1981/04/24","","Day",<p>Reagan lifts a grain embargo imposed on Soviet Union by President Carter. </p>
"1981/07/07","","Day",<p>Reagan nominates Sandra Day O'Connor to fill the seat of retiring Supreme Court justice Potter Stewart, making O'Connor the first woman to sit on the Supreme Court. </p>
"1981/08/05","","Day",<p>Reagan orders the dismissal of 13,000 PATCO air traffic controllers out on strike, citing their violation of a federal law against industry strikes. </p>
"1981/08/13","","Day",<p>Reagan signs the tax cut into law. </p>
"1981/10/02","","Day",<p>Reagan declares that the United States will produce the B-1 bomber and MX missiles as part of military buildup. </p>
"1981/11/18","","Day",<p>Reagan states that he will not deploy intermediate-range nuclear missiles in Europe if the Soviet Union agrees to dismantle similar weapons already in place. </p>
"1981/12/28","","Day",<p>Reagan imposes economic sanctions on Poland following that government's imposition of martial law. </p>
"1982/01/26","","Day",<p>Reagan calls for "New Federalism" in his State of the Union address, advocating less federal spending and more state initiative to solve social and economic problems. </p>
"1982/06/06","","Day",<p>Reagan becomes the first U.S. President to address the combined Houses of Parliament, taking Britain's side in the Falkland Islands conflict with Argentina. </p>
"1982/06/11","","Day",<p>Reagan visits West Berlin. </p>
"1982/06/30","","Day",<p>Reagan establishes the President's Private Sector Survey on Cost Control through Executive Order 12369. </p>
"1982/09/03","","Day",<p>Reagan signs the Tax Equity & Fiscal Responsibility Act (TEFRA). </p>
"1983/01/05","","Day",<p>Reagan signs into law a five cents per gallon gasoline tax increase. </p>
"1983/01/25","","Day",<p>In his State of the Union address, Reagan calls for a freeze on domestic spending and increases in military outlays. </p>
"1983/03/23","","Day",<p>Reagan urges development of the Strategic Defense Initiative (SDI), an attempt to create a high-technology anti-ballistic missile shield to protect the United States from nuclear attack. </p>
"1983/04/20","","Day",<p>President Reagan signs the Social Security Reform Bill into law. </p>
"1983/04/20","","Day",<p>The U.S. GNP shows dramatic growth for the first quarter of 1983, signaling the end of the recession. </p>
"1983/06/18","","Day",<p>Reagan nominates Paul Volcker to a second term as head of the Federal Reserve Board. </p>
"1983/07/01","","Day",<p>The final phase of the tax cut goes into effect. </p>
"1984/01/25","","Day",<p>Reagan delivers State of the Union message, calling on Congress to cooperate to reduce the deficit. </p>
"1984/04/30","","Day",<p>Reagan signs scientific and cultural exchange accords with the Beijing leadership while on six-day visit to China. </p>
"1984/08/22","","Day",<p> The Republican Party re-nominates Reagan and Bush for 1984 presidential election. </p>
"1984/09/21","","Day",<p>Congress and Reagan work out a compromise on the MX missile. </p>
"1984/11/06","","Day",<p>Reagan is reelected President, defeating Democratic candidate Walter Mondale. </p>
"1985/01/20","","Day",<p>Reagan is inaugurated for a second term as President of the United States. </p>
"1985/02/06","","Day",<p>Farm credit crises pose serious a threat to U.S. agriculture. The Reagan administration eases rules on a loan-guarantee program, but rejects provisions for additional funding. </p>
"1985/05/01","","Day",<p>The Reagan administration announces trade embargo against Nicaragua. </p>
"1985/05/05","","Day",<p>Reagan attends a wreath-laying ceremony at Bitburg military cemetery in West Germany, the gravesite of 200 German soldiers including 49 members of Adolf Hitler's SS. Responding to criticism of the visit, Reagan visits and lays a wreath at a nearby concentration camp earlier in the day. </p>
"1985/07/13","","Day",<p>Reagan has a malignant polyp removed from his colon; Vice President Bush serves as acting President for eight hours. </p>
"1985/09/09","","Day",<p>The Reagan administration announces limited economic sanctions against South Africa after the South African government declares martial law. </p>
"1985/11/19","11 19-21, 1985","Day",<p>Reagan and Soviet premier Mikhail Gorbachev hold a summit meeting in Geneva, Switzerland. It is the first such meeting between U.S and Soviet heads of state since 1979. </p>
"1985/12/12","","Day",<p>Reagan signs the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction bill. </p>
"1986/06/17","","Day",<p>Supreme Court Chief Justice Warren Burger announces his retirement; Regan elevates Justice William Rehnquist to the position of chief justice and nominates Anthony Scalia as an associate justice. </p>
"1986/10/11","1986/10/12","Day",<p>Reagan and Gorbachev meet in Reykjavik, Iceland. </p>
"1986/10/22","","Day",<p>Reagan signs a revision of the tax code into law. </p>
"1986/11/04","","Day",<p>The Democrats win control of Senate, the first time during Reagan's tenure that both houses of Congress are in Democratic hands. </p>
"1986/11/13","","Day",<p>The White House informs Congress that the United States secretly sold arms to Iran in violation of federal laws prohibiting arms deals with Iran. The administration denies that the sales were part of an attempt to secure the release of American hostages held by Iranian-backed forces. </p>
"1986/11/25","","Day",<p>The administration admits that between $10 and $30 million had been diverted from Iranian arms sales and funneled to the Nicaraguan contras. </p>
"1986/11/26","","Day",<p>The Tower Commission is appointed to investigate the Iran-Contra affair. Reagan forgoes any claim of executive privilege and orders his administration to cooperate fully with the investigation. Lawrence Walsh is appointed special prosecutor to investigate criminal wrongdoing. </p>
"1987/02/03","1987/02/04","Day",<p>Congress overrides Reagan's veto of the Water Quality Control Act. </p>
"1987/02/26","","Day",<p>The Tower Commission releases its report, finding no criminal wrongdoing on the part of the White House but remaining critical of the administration nonetheless. </p>
"1987/03/04","","Day",<p>In televised address, Reagan accepts responsibility for actions in Iran-Contra affair that occurred without his knowledge. </p>
"1987/11/18","","Day",<p>Congress issues its Iran-Contra report, declaring that Regan must assume "ultimate responsibility" for the affair. </p>
"1987/12/07","1987/12/10","Day",<p>Gorbachev and Reagan meet in Washington, D.C., and sign the Intermediate Range Nuclear Forces Treaty. </p>
"1988/01/29","","Day",<p>The administration prohibits federally funded family-planning centers from providing assistance to women seeking abortions. </p>
"1988/05/29","1988/06/01","Day",<p>Reagan visits the Soviet Union for the first time. </p>
"1988/08/15","1988/08/18","Day",<p>The Republican Party nominates George H.W. Bush and Dan Quayle for President and vice president. </p>
"1988/11/08","","Day",<p>Vice President George H.W. Bush is elected President of the United States, defeating Democratic challenger Michael Dukakis. </p>
"1989/01/11","","Day",<p>Reagan delivers his farewell address. </p>
"1989/01/20","","Day",<p>Reagan leaves office with public opinion casting him as the nation's most popular President since Franklin D. Roosevelt. </p>
